Note that we can do multiple operations on the same index. For example, on index i we can subtract a_{i-1} multiple times? Actually, we can do:

      Operation 1: set a_i = a_i - a_{i-1} Then if we do again: set a_i = (a_i - a_{i-1}) - a_{i-1} = a_i - 2*a_{i-1}

  So effectively, we can subtract any multiple of a_{i-1} from a_i. Therefore, we can set a_i to any nonnegative value of the form a_i mod a_{i-1} (if we do enough subtractions, we get the remainder, but note: we can only subtract so we get nonnegative remainders? Actually, the problem does not say we can get negative, but the operation is defined as a_i - a_{i-1} and we can do any number of times.

